NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|You rarely get a good result letting the opponents play at the one level. If you can beat them at the one level, you can usually make something yourself. So, you increase your odds by balancing. Every once in a while, you will get too high, and turn a plus into a minus, but more often than not, you will turn a minus into a plus.  My feeling is that you should pretty much never let the opponents play at the one level, unless you have a real stack in their suit. Basically, you need to understand the theory of balancing.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|The idea is that if the auction goes 1 something, pass, pass, the points are pretty evenly split. Now, if you are in pass out seat, even with as little as 6 or 7 points, partner must have a pretty good hand, at least 11 or 12. So, when you "balance", that is make a bid in pass out seat, you are bidding for the entire partnership, not just your hand. The worse your hand, the more likely the better partner's hand is. It works out that way almost all of the time, as it did on this hand. kia rightfully passed with a 12 count, and joyce had 10, so they had a majority of the points.|
