NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|If I open one of a minor, and partner bids one of a major, and the intervening opponent makes an overcall or double, some people play a convention known as "support double/redouble." If the intervening bid is a double, a redouble by me shows 3 card support for the major. And if the intervening bid is an overcall (1@S for example), a double by me shows 3 card support. In other words, the double or redouble shows exactly 3 card support for the major, whereas a raise would guarantee 4 card support. Once I show 3 card support, moe has a great hand and rightfully bids 4 hearts.|
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Now, as to the play, moe needs to plan the hand out slightly better. He has a potential loser in spades, in  hearts, and up to 2 diamond losers. He can get rid of his spade loser on the club, if he plans carefully. I think what he should do, at trick 2, play a club to the K, and then play a heart to the K.  Then he can play the A of clubs, pitching his spade loser. Then, he can ruff a spade back to his hand, and play a diamond towards the Q.  That pretty much guarantees the contract no matter what.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Now, a comment on the defense. When joyce gets in with the K of diamonds, a spade back is pretty clear.  Partner led the K of spades, so joyce knows he has the Q and she should make sure their side gets their spade trick. So the two important points are:
1) Plan the hand out at trick one, counting your losers and figuring out how to get rid of them. Although your first instinct should be to draw trumps, sometimes you have to delay in order to take care of other losers
2) Once your partner picks a defense, you should stick to it, unless there is a real good reason to switch.|
