^C@2New minor forcing (NMF) is a convention that is used to discover a major suit fit after opener has rebid 1N or @E@32N after opening one of a minor and receiving a response of one of a major. 

Example auctions would be 1@D-P-1H-P-1N or 1@C-P-1@S--2N. If you decide to play NMF, then if responder bids the other minor (clubs if the opening bid was diamonds, and diamonds if the opening bid was clubs), that is the new minor forcing convention. 

Opener is asked to describe his length in the majors. If he has 4 cards in the unbid major, he bids that suit. If he has 3 card support for the major bid by responder, he raises responder (note that opener can not have 4 cards in responder's major, because he would have raised immediately rather than bidding NT). 

If he has both, you need to have some agreement. I recommend that opener prefer bidding the 4 card major rather than showing 3 card support.

As an example, let us use the auction 1@C-P-1@H-P-1N-P-2@D-P. Opener would bid 2@H with 3 card heart support, 2@S with 4 spades (if he has both, I recommend opener bid 2@S), and 2N with neither.

Note that if opener has both the other 4 card major and 3 card support, and responder returns to NT, opener is obligated to return to the suit he did not bid. So, if the auction goes 1@C-P-1@H-P-1N-P-2@D-P-2@S-P-3N, opener should bid 4 hearts if he has 3 card heart support. The reason is responder will only bid NMF if he has a 5 card major or the other major (or both); with the auction in question, responder must have 5 hearts.|
