^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his @E@3important instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls" which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you will find many more.|fp|2|at| 

**  You rarely get a good result letting the opponents play at the one level. If you can beat them at the one level, you can usually make something yourself. So, you increase your odds by balancing.

**  You should pretty much never let the opponents play at the one level, unless you have a real stack in their suit.

**  When you "balance", that is make a bid in pass out seat, you are bidding for the entire partnership, not just your hand.

**  Once your partner picks a defense, you should stick to it, unless there is a real good reason to switch.

